---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import CostChart from "../components/CostChart.astro";
import { accuracyRows, benchmarkRows, benchmarkSummary } from "../facts";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Benchmarks · Squeezy"
  description="Measured Squeezy cost, graph accuracy, and benchmark caveats from checked-in repository data."
  active="benchmarks"
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">benchmarks</span>
      <h1>Show the savings and the losses.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        The public benchmark story is intentionally narrow: one checked-in
        Mini suite, every language row visible, and accuracy caveats next to
        the charts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header wide">
      <span class="eyebrow">cost data</span>
      <h2>{benchmarkSummary.totalDelta} lower total spend across the measured Mini suite.</h2>
      <p>
        {benchmarkSummary.suite} Squeezy was cheaper on {benchmarkSummary.wins}
        rows and at parity or more expensive on {benchmarkSummary.losses} rows.
        A win requires 100% measured recall and at least a 5% lower cost.
      </p>
    </div>
    <CostChart rows={benchmarkRows} />
    <p class="footnote">
      Source: <code>docs/internal/eval-findings/mini-vs-codex-realworld.csv</code>.
      Squeezy cost includes parent and delegate subagent spend. This is not a
      universal provider-independent savings claim.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section band">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">what the chart means</span>
      <h2>The graph helps when code discovery would otherwise become context-heavy.</h2>
      <p>
        The best public reading is practical: graph navigation can lower model
        spend on multi-file code-navigation tasks, but the graph is not free.
        Small or read-heavy tasks can sit near parity or lose.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-3">
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">include losses</span>
        <h3>Four rows are not wins</h3>
        <p>C#, Go, Java, and Ruby are shown as losses or near-parity rows in the checked-in CSV. Hiding them would overstate the product.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">quality first</span>
        <h3>Cost alone is not enough</h3>
        <p>The benchmark only counts a win when recall holds. Cheaper wrong answers are not treated as product wins.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">task scope</span>
        <h3>This is code navigation data</h3>
        <p>The suite measures real-world navigation prompts across languages. It does not claim every editing, debugging, or creative task is cheaper.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">graph validation</span>
      <h2>Benchmarks also measure whether local graph evidence is accurate.</h2>
      <p>
        Squeezy uses compiler and language-service oracles in benchmark mode to
        check local tree-sitter graph output. Those oracles are validation
        tools, not production navigation dependencies.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="matrix">
      {
        accuracyRows.map((row) => (
          <article class="matrix-row">
            <div><h3>{row.name}</h3></div>
            <p>{row.detail}</p>
            {row.status && <span class="status-pill ok">{row.status}</span>}
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact band">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">methodology guardrails</span>
      <h2>What not to infer from this page.</h2>
      <p>
        Do not read this as "Squeezy is always cheaper" or "the graph has
        perfect code understanding." The current safe claim is that Squeezy has
        a measured cost-saving path for code navigation, with the data and
        losses published beside the claim.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
